OnTrack Rust binaries can be cross-compiled for multiple platforms from a single host machine.

## Supported Targets

| Target Triple | Platform | CLI | GUI |
|--------------|----------|-----|-----|
| `x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu` | Linux x86_64 | Yes | Yes |
| `aarch64-unknown-linux-gnu` | Linux ARM64 | Yes | Yes |
| `x86_64-apple-darwin` | macOS Intel | Yes | Yes |
| `aarch64-apple-darwin` | macOS Apple Silicon | Yes | Yes |
| `x86_64-pc-windows-gnu` | Windows x86_64 | Yes | Limited |

GUI cross-compilation for Windows is limited because egui's system dependencies require manual setup of the MinGW windowing libraries.

## Using cross-rs (Recommended)

[cross-rs](https://github.com/cross-rs/cross) uses Docker containers with pre-configured toolchains for each target.

### Install

```bash
cargo install cross --git https://github.com/cross-rs/cross
```

### Build

```bash
cd ontrack-rs

# Single target
cross build --release --target aarch64-unknown-linux-gnu

# Using the build script
../scripts/cross-compile-rs.sh --target aarch64-unknown-linux-gnu

# All targets
../scripts/cross-compile-rs.sh --all
```

## Using cargo (Native Targets Only)

Without cross-rs, cargo can build for targets that match your host toolchain:

```bash
# Add the target
rustup target add aarch64-unknown-linux-gnu

# Build (requires a linker for the target)
cargo build --release --target aarch64-unknown-linux-gnu
```

You need the appropriate cross-linker installed:
- `aarch64-linux-gnu-gcc` for ARM64 Linux
- Xcode for macOS targets (must build on macOS)

## Build Script

The `scripts/cross-compile-rs.sh` script automates the process:

```bash
# Build CLI only for a specific target
./scripts/cross-compile-rs.sh --target x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu --cli-only

# Build everything for all targets
./scripts/cross-compile-rs.sh --all

# List available targets
./scripts/cross-compile-rs.sh --list
```

Binaries are placed in `dist/<target>/`:

```
dist/
├── x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu/
│   ├── ontrack
│   └── ontrack-gui
├── aarch64-unknown-linux-gnu/
│   └── ontrack
└── x86_64-pc-windows-gnu/
    └── ontrack.exe
```

## Master Build Script

`scripts/build-all.sh` builds both Python and Rust:

```bash
# Build everything for host
./scripts/build-all.sh --all

# Build Rust with cross-compilation
./scripts/build-all.sh --rust --target aarch64-unknown-linux-gnu

# List all available targets
./scripts/build-all.sh --list-targets
```

## Nix-Based Cross-Compilation

The Nix flake can build for any of its supported systems:

```bash
# Build for a specific system
nix build .#packages.aarch64-linux.ontrack-rs-cli

# Build and check everything
./scripts/nix-build-all.sh --all
```

## Tips

- **macOS targets** can only be built natively on macOS due to Apple SDK requirements
- **Windows targets** work best for CLI-only builds; GUI requires MinGW windowing libs
- **ARM64 Linux** builds work well with cross-rs from any Linux host
- **Static linking** via `RUSTFLAGS="-C target-feature=+crt-static"` produces binaries with no runtime dependencies (Linux/Windows only)
